[]: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Quote Post by FreakyFilmFan4ever &raquo; Mon Aug 12, 2013 6:42 pm I was new to anime in general when I first saw NGE in 2009. &#40;It was only the 3rd or 4th anime title I had seen at the time.&#41; I was really liking what I saw. So half way through it, I did some research on Evangelion, just to see how much of the series there was left to watch. I saw that after the TV series there was 2 movies completing it, then 4 proposed movies, 2 of them had already been made. To be honest, my heart sank. I assumed this meant that Eva was gonna be like Gundum, an anime I had intentionally avoided because I didn&#39;t want to have to sit through literally hundreds of episodes and thousands of hours of continuity and canon in order to just watch a TV show. I didn&#39;t want Evangelion to span many generations with different protagonists piloting Evas. This show worked way too well as a character study to suddenly turn it into a vessel for mindless action scenes featuring stock anime characters. I seriously thought about dropping the whole show right then and there. But I kept watching for some reason. Eva&#39;s like that; once you start you can&#39;t ever stop, no matter what your opinion of the show might be at the time. &#40;I think that&#39;s one of the show&#39;s greatest strengths.&#41; So, I was surprised when the series most definitely ended with 25, 26, and EoE. There was absolutely no room for a sequel after that. I mean, now what? On a superficial level, all of your Eva Units are either dead or lost in space, Nerv and Seele don&#39;t exist in human form anymore, Rei somehow became a 100-mile high goddess before breaking into a million pieces, and, oh yeah, sans Asuka and Shinji all of humanity is now stew in the oceans. What&#39;s your next trick for the other 4 movies, guys? Is Asuka gonna merge with Kyoko and start swallowing entire galaxies? Knowing that it would be impossible in this continuity for Asuka to do such a thing, I went back and read up on the new &quot;Rebuild&quot; movies and found out that they were remakes instead of continuations. &#40;Yeah, I know people are still debating that. But whatever. If entire galaxies aren&#39;t being swallowed in FINAL, then it fails at being a sequel simply based on the idea that sequels need to be bigger and bolder than the first installment.&#41; What made me more excited was that it was the same creative team making the remakes. Cecil B. DeMille and Alfred Hitchcock did the same thing with a few of their selected works, and they managed to turn out a product better than their first time at telling the story. Since no one knew the works better than these guys, I can&#39;t imagine then screwing it up. And so far I&#39;ve been enjoying these newer movies. It definitely has the same spirit and core appeal of the original show &#40;especially with Q&#41; while also managing to be a completely different story told in a bit more emotionally stable way than the first one. &#40;Even though the emotional instability of the NGE is one of the reasons why I like it so much, a more stable approach to NTE doesn&#39;t cause it to lose anything vital to the franchise.&#41;
